fields.label_text: The chimney piece came from a house in Antwerp. On the projecting hood are carved grotesque terminal figures and three cartouches, the central one containing an unidentified coat of arms and the flanking ones allegorical figures apparently representing (left) Neptune and (right) Ceres. These and all the decorative masks that punctuate the composition are excellently carved and recall work by Cornelius Floris.

fields.descriptive_line: Chimney Piece, marble and stone, ca. 1550, South Netherlands
fields.physical_description:
Above the entablature is a projecting hood of convex form carved with terminal figures and three cartouches, the centre one containing a shield of arms the others nude male and female figures. 
The back of the fire place is built-up of 168 terracotta bricks of Dutch or Flemish manufacture (some of them modern imitations), with Scripture subjects in relief. On the top of these is a larger brick, triangular headed, bearing the arms of Charles V., his motto "Plus oltre", and date 1552.

fields.public_access_description:
This chimney piece of marble and stone is made by an unknown artist ca. 1550 in the South of the Netherlands.

The back of the fire place is built-up of 168 terracotta bricks of Dutch or Flemish manufacture (some of them modern imitations).

The chimney piece came from a house in Antwerp. On the projecting hood are carved grotesque terminal figures and three cartouches, the central one containing an unidentified coat of arms and the flanking ones allegorical figures apparently representing (left) Neptune and (right) Ceres. These and all the decorative masks that punctuate the composition are excellently carved and recall work by Cornelius Floris.
